, Adrian Bunk wrote:<br />&gt; <br />&gt; If you think we have too many stacksize problems I'd suggest to consider <br />&gt; removing the choice of 4k stacks on i386, sh and m68knommu instead of <br />&gt; using -fno-inline-functions-called-once:<br /><br />Don't be silly. That makes the problem _worse_.<br /><br />We're much better off with a 1% code-size reduction than forcing big <br />stacks on people. The 4kB stack option is also a good way of saying "if it <br />works with this, then 8kB is certainly safe".<br /><br />And embedded people (the ones that might care about 1% code size) are the <br />ones that would also want smaller stacks even more!<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
